# Knock Detector

An edge AI device that listens for door knocks and provides a visual alert.
Built for CASA0018: Deep Learning for Sensor Networks.

**Author:** Finlay Miller
**Module:** CASA0018, UCL Bartlett Centre for Advanced Spatial Analysis

## Project summary

More than 18 million adults in the UK are deaf or have hearing loss. For this population, an unanswered knock at the door means a missed visitor, delivery, or emergency. Smart doorbells only solve this when visitors press the button — and around half don't.

This project is a low-power embedded device that listens for knocks using a 1D convolutional neural network running entirely on an Arduino Nano 33 BLE Sense. When a knock is detected, the LED turns red and a Bluetooth notification is sent to a paired phone.

## Results

| Metric | Value |
|---|---|
| Test accuracy | 93.98% |
| Knock recall | 91.7% |
| False positive rate | 3.9% |
| AUC | 0.94 |
| RAM usage on Arduino | 15.4 KB |
| Flash usage on Arduino | 30.4 KB |
| End-to-end inference latency | 157 ms |

## How it works

Audio is captured by the onboard PDM microphone at 16 kHz in 1-second windows. Each window is converted to 13 MFCC coefficients across 50 frames, classified by a small 1D CNN, and gated by a 0.85 confidence threshold. The device persists in alert state until acknowledged via a Bluetooth Low Energy write from a paired phone.

